{"text": "There's been a lot of negativity surrrounding this game. I think that people want to see something different from Sonic. I'm enjoying it for what it is, though. It may not be Mario Odyssey or Sonic Mania. But, that's the thing--it's not TRYING to be any of those games and I think that's the way it should be.  It delivers in what it's trying to deliver but not in some ways that others may prefer. Anyway, I just beat the game and started the Episode Shadow DLC.  Pros (not in any particular order): + Soundtrack/ I don't listen to the genres of music that are in this game but it sounds really good and it matches the gameplay well. + Graphics/ The stages look really nice. The backgrounds for the stages are definitely better than any other Sonic game BY FAR. This provides for a great atmosphere when traversing through stages at high speeds. The game's not about sight-seeing, though, which brings me to the next point-- + SPEED-BASED gameplay/ Even though the gameplay style is the same as Sonic Generations and Sonic Colors, the level design felt a bit different. Not really in a good or bad way. It was just a bit different. Closer to Colors than Generations, though. Definitely.  People complained about this game being \"linear.\" That's not true. If you play this and think it's linear, then you need to GIT GUD because alternative paths are available for those with quick eyes and reflexes--in other words, you'll miss them if you don't react fast enough. Also, bringing new weapons to the stages with your custom character opens up new paths. It gives the game a sense of variety in how stages are played. Honestly, the stages are short but they feel oddly satisfying--no need to be going through 5-minute stages when they have such replay value. The game isn't meant to be played like an open world game where you explore and poke around every corner. Actually, according to Yuji Naka, the creator of Sonic, the original concept of Sonic the Hedgehog was to get to the end of each stage as quickly as possible.  Story/ It was a GREAT story! It was well-written with some strangely thought-provoking lines in it. It's really not as dark as people are saying it is. It's better described as having a \"dark setting\" with a \"light-hearted\" tone. The world is taken over by the main villain Eggman but everyone's still cracking jokes and having a good laugh here and there. Nothing inappropriate for youngsters here but definitely nothing too cheesy for us older folks to enjoy. Side note for any die-hard fans: Imagine if Sonic Team decided to take the best ideas from the old SatAM cartoon and the Archie comic books and reinvent them for a new story that only includes the cast from the game series and your own custom character. That would be the best way to describe this story. Cons: - Short game/ It took me about 6 hours to beat the main story and I had replayed stages a lot to get S ranks. I also took time to play some extra stages. But, something tells me that they might be adding more to it with future DLC. Maybe, maybe not. This remains a con until we see that. - Speed-based gameplay/ This game is definitely not for everyone. Don't pick this up if you like platforming games with wide-open levels. Sonic Forces is something that can be enjoyed by someone who plays it with the mindset that getting through the stage quickly brings rewards. Running as fast as you can to get to the end of the stage as quickly as possible--That's what this is about. Not exploration. Yes, finding collectables takes multiple playthroughs and using different paths will help to find them. I had a blast playing this game but that won't be the same for everyone because of this. - Obviously shoehorned-in element/ As much as I'm against the biased criticisms that are being given to this title--I have to admit that classic Sonic really did seem out of place. It probably would've been nicer to see the game with just the avatar character and Modern Sonic only. It would've made much more sense, too.  Some closing thoughts: After playing, I realized that I enjoyed playing as my custom character more than even modern Sonic with Classic Sonic being my least favorite to play with (though, I also enjoyed Classic Sonic's stages). The custom character aspect really gives off the feeling of putting you, the player, in the world of Sonic and I like that. My wife was watching me play and every time she referred to the custom character, she would say that it was \"me\" instead of the \"rookie\" or the \"custom character.\" Honestly, I didn't care as much for this aspect when they announced it but surprisingly--I enjoyed it most in the end. Something not positive or negative: Modern Sonic lost his drift (from Generations) and I wondered why until after playing a few of the custom character stages and realizing that the drift was set to the triggers just like the custom character's weapon (or wispon) is set to the right trigger so it was probably a design choice to remove the drift to make room for the tag team stages. I mean, someone could probably argue that they could've just made the drift useable with only 1 trigger (that being the left trigger) but that could feel uncomfortable for some, I'm sure--as it would be for myself. Maybe they considered that. Maybe they were being lazy. Who knows? Still I never felt like I wanted to use the drift during game. It never felt necessary so that's fine with me.  If I'd give this a rating, I'd say it's about an 8/10. I feel like it's going to grow on me, though. I might update this after 100% completing it.  Quick edit: Even as I write this, I have this crazy urge to go back into the game and replay some of the stages over and over again (I just finished playing about an hour ago) and unlike most Sonic games, I don't have specific stages in-mind that I want to revisit--this is a good sign--as it goes to show how consistent the quality of each stage in Sonic Forces is.  - LB", "appid": "637100", "steamid": "profiles/76561198051843105", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "8", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1510056000.0}
