{"text": "The best of the classic build engine games, readily accessible without the need to set up a source port or server for multiplayer. BLOOD perfects the formula started with Duke Nukem 3D, with some of the fluid, nuanced combat ever put into an FPS game.  The setting for this action is a beautifully realized gothic horror version of the 1920s, taking you through a variety of locations, ranging from Carnivals and Cities to Castles and Cursed Manors. Each setting brings with it a unique atmosphere, brought to life by the Build Engine's ability to create pixelated locales that you can physically relate to as real spaces. If one is paying attention to the events that transpire, they can notice the hopelessness that stems from the monolothic nature of the enemy; a cult that has either infiltrated or is in the process of terrorizing almost every rung of society, with an economic and industrial base run by mad scientists, all put towards the singular purpose of serving their dark god. The situation lends itself only to a violent solution, and the protagonist, Caleb is happy to oblige, serving as your avatar in this classic story of revenge driven rampage.  Your arsenal is equal parts creative, deadly and satisfying, with every piece of equipment you have fulfilling some kind of utility, allowing you to strategize your way out of the plethora of deadly encounters you will face. One of your basic weapons, the Dynamite bundle, is a great example of BLOOD's approach to weapon design. Upon first inspection, the weapon is a basic thrown explosive, much like the grenades in any other game. After your first toss, you find that you can control the arc and force of your throw by holding down the mouse button, timing and aim being important to practice, as it becomes one of your workhorse weapons throughout the game. When you try out your alternate fire, you have your first taste of the dual usage the Weapons have to offer, making the weapon complexity already, much more pronounced than similar titles like Duke Nukem 3D or Shadow Warrior. Your alternate fire lights your fuse and grants the bundle the ability to bounce, rather than explode on impact. You learn that direct explosions are great for certain enemies and situations, with many tankier foes rewarding a well placed impact with a quick, ammo efficient death. On the other hand, your secondary bounce excels at indirect fire, whether to check potentially dangerous rooms or initiate plans of attack, out-ambushing the hitscanners hoping to perforate your unsuspecting hero. Now, you will have to practice your aim, understanding of physics and the timing of both your fuse and throw. All of this complexity is found just in your first weapon, made all the sweeter by the game's lovingly crafted spritework and sound design.  The enemies you slaughter with these weapons are as creative and nuanced to match, with the game's iconic Cultists serving as the main event. These robed soldiers of evil are well deserving of a spot next to DOOM's Demons, Half-Life's HECU Marines or F.E.A.R.'s Replicas in the hall of fame of FPS AI you love to kill. With superb aim and high damage, these hitscanners are designed to create barriers against the poorly planned approach, often punishing this behaviour faster than the victim can react. BLOOD requires you to use your utility, mobility and tactics to conquer their numbers. Your Tommy Gun can stunlock the Cultists, buying you time to duck and weave under their shots and into cover. Your Dynamite and it's variants can be used to set traps, bypass choke points and clear large groups at once. Your Flare Gun can be used to punish foes for grouping up too close or at ranges where your firearms are less reliable. Each of your Shotgun's (one of the most satisfying ever put into a game) barrels can be used either one at a time or together in order to ward off aggression and thin out their numbers with quick flick aimed shots at medium range. That is all just to name some of the options available to you. If executed right, your plans will result in a shower of gore, punctuated by the hilariously exaggerated  screams of your enemies, their occult speech devolving into primal cries and mortal language in their last moments, reduced to this pitiful state from your assorted box of torture. All your wretched foes will react in sweet accordance to your choice of either burning, shooting, exploding, electrocuting, stabbing or occult magic. Couple this with open level design and high levels of vertical and horizontal mobility and you setup an addictive gameplay loop that leaves the player begging for more. Luckily, Fresh Supply comes prepared with the tools for more BLOOD donations, with modding support, allowing veterans of the base game and it's expansions to dig into a variety of fan created content. As of this writing, I am currently playing through the fan expansion Death Wish, featuring over 30 levels crafted with the same level of love and care as the original game. BLOOD: Fresh Supply may have started off as a rocky port, but ample patches have created an experience faithful to the original 1997 classic with added quality of life features for online-play, modern settings and hassle-free, install and play setup. You will get nothing out of this review short of an emphatic recommendation to experience the ultra-violent gothic nightmare that is BLOOD.", "appid": "1010750", "steamid": "profiles/76561198015279513", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "20", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1594209600.0}
