{"text": "By the time Dragon Age: Origins had released in November of 2009, Bioware had already made the case that they were wholly capable of trailblazing the Western RPG. They had released Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic in 2003, Jade Empire in 2005, and most famously, Mass Effect in 2007. If it wasn’t clear prior to this, it soon would be: Bioware was establishing itself as a video game pantheon for storytelling and the entire landscape of modern RPGs. Dragon Age: Origins was more proof. The final piece of evidence submitted. Bioware was on fire, and nothing – except eventually themselves – would ever hold them back. DA:O really amounts to Bioware’s version of Baldur’s Gate III with seventh-generation modernization updates. The game allows you to create a man, dwarf, or elf, of either sex, while also allowing the player to choose each character’s individual origin and class. The origins for each character vary significantly so no choice feels superfluous, and they all add incentive for re-playablity. The scope of customization will seem incredibly familiar to anyone coming to this game in 2020, but for its time, the sheer depth of customization wasn’t entirely mainstream. For many gamers, particularly those that were relegated to consoles in the early 2000s, RPG exposure came primarily from the East. I was one of those people, and as such, I can speak from experience. The malleable nature of crafting the narrative through my own choices, and customizing every granular detail about my hero felt completely novel, even if it wasn’t. To me, an RPG meant something more akin to Final Fantasy – not what Bioware had on offer here.    The story is about stopping something known as “The Blight.” An era when Darkspawn, sharing many attributes with Orcs from The Lord of the Rings, unleash havoc across all the kingdoms of Thedas. You play as a Grey Warden, one of an ancient order of knights sworn to kill Darkspawn and end The Blight. This blight is not the first. They have come and go, slipping in and out of legend. If The Blight should appear, the Grey Warden shall end it. It’s generic high fantasy, and those familiar with the tropes that are usually contained within this genre won’t find anything particularly original here. That isn’t a criticism. There’s a reason why these tropes have existed for so long – they work. Ending The Blight isn’t even the story, not really. The game is about recruiting a team of elite warriors and settling a civil war before The Blight can even be dealt with. As with most stories that show a civilization on the brink, the inhabitants won't stop tearing themselves apart long enough to deal with the true threat.  This is where DA:O shines brightest. Each recruit takes you on a mission – and each mission is unique. The time spent with the characters on these quests, in desperation and in battle, are a marvel and, for the time, mostly original. When each mission ends, you’re granted time at camp, around a bonfire, and have the opportunity to meet with each party member. You discuss the day’s events or sit and palaver on deeper subjects – or more intimate ones. And there’s agency given to each interaction because the characters you surround yourself with don’t always like what you have to say. If you harangue someone for their inability, or make a sexual pass at someone who isn’t receptive – you need to be willing to live with the consequence of that. And it all feels character-based. There’s little winking and nodding. The characters behave in a way that makes sense for who they are. Bioware’s ability to craft this characterization was nothing short of incredible, particularly for 2009. And while they would later perfect this style of storytelling in the recruiting missions and Normandy walkthroughs from 2010’s Mass Effect 2, its roots still grew incredibly deep here. It’s really something more RPGs should do – if they have the aptitude.    The combat is archaic by modern standards. It’s still deeply entrenched in the Baldur’s Gate formula that came before it. The characters auto-attack, and separately you can use abilities by clicking the corresponding button that triggers it. There’s a lot of rinse and repeat here. Fights rarely play uniquely. Most doors open revealing a horde of enemies. You dispense with that horde. Then you open the next door. And so on. Whether this becomes monotonous or not is going to depend on the individual. It never bothers me; I enjoy the mechanics and build variety so much that the nature of how each character is controlled works. But I’ve also played the games that inspired it. It’s frankly arguable whether DA:O’s combat has more in common with its isometric predecessors than even subsequent Dragon Age games. Bugs run amok in DA:O. I encountered several texture issues and graphical glitches when playing on Steam. I’ve been told it has to do with memory leak, but didn’t bother verifying it. I also experienced several crashes, particularly when the game would move in and out of cutscenes, although it didn’t require that. The game is older now, and is complicated further because it came from a generation where such annoyances were omnipresent. Sometimes a game is good enough to look past these inconveniences and sometimes it isn’t. For me, DA:O is now and was then – but it’s something anyone coming to the game in 2020 know.  I’ve probably played DA:O three or four times throughout the course of my life. And every time, I’m flooded with nostalgia, but not without a pinch of disappointment. The game is clunky. And it never sheds the feeling of being rushed. As an example, moving from room to room in a random evil tower will feel eerily similar to what you just did just a few hours ago in an environment that was supposedly 100 miles away. And the same enemies occupy both. It adds an occasional redundancy to your objectives even when you’re having fun. There's a sadness looking back on this game and seeing the pieces come together, but not completely clicking in place. Why? Because the game was made by Bioware, and knowing the reputation they had at the time, and now having the full grasp of hindsight and history, it’s regretful knowing that this was the best Dragon Age we got. Every piece of this game’s potential displays a promise that should have been fulfilled in future sequels. That didn't happen. I’m always excited to play the next Dragon Age game. And that has little to do with anything that came after this entry. It’s big praise to say that something that came out 11 years ago still has fans hoping that the lightning can be recaptured in the bottle. DA:O, to my estimation, was simply the best RPG that Bioware had done to that point. That’s not to say I dislike the sequels that came after; I don’t. In fact, I probably like Dragon Age sequels more than most, but it’s no secret that Bioware never built on momentum that was established in DA:O. We’re all still stuck waiting. One wonders if the sequels had been better, would DA:O be looked upon in an even greater light?  What we have here was one of the finest RPGs of its generation. A solid story, featuring excellent character development and some of the best world building one can still find. While it is occasionally messy in its delivery, it carved out as good of a foundation as the first game in a series could do. It may lack polish, but never heart. It was one for 2009. And it’s one for 2020.", "appid": "47810", "steamid": "profiles/76561198081614663", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "30", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1593432000.0}
