{"text": "Hellblade: Senua's Sacrifice is a over-the-shoulder third-person story-driven adventure.       9/10 -- Zynbel The setting is the mind of Senua, her mind creates a warped version of reality and the game takes place in the Nordic realm of Hel, ruled by the godess of the same name. -- The narrator/voice Senua suffers from Psychosis, meaning she struggles to tell the difference between what is reality and what is not. After the death of her, Dillion, who was killed by Viking raiders, Senua embarks on a journey to the realm of Hel to recover the soul of Dillion in an effort to bring him back. It's a quest to recover Dillion but throughout this quest, Senua struggles with her Psychosis as she travels deeper into Hel, filled with Demons and the darkness forever breaking her mind. There's not much more I can say without spoiling it, it's easily one of the best games I've played this year (2018). -- Druth The level design is one of the best parts of this game. The world itself is stunning, along with an awesome background in the distance. I admit the rock textures aren't the best, even at max settings, everything else is amazing. Little things like the lighting, foliage & water make the world feel so immersive. It all adds to the dark, modody and depression atmosphere of the game, the display how dark and twisted Senuas Psychosis really is. -- Dillion The gameplay is fairly limited and the lest-interesting part of the game. The combat feels great & there's enough combat situations within the game to keep you engaged. There isn't much interactions to actually do in the game and the few that there is are there to serve as functions to progress the game forward, such as opening doors. Overall, it's really good, there's just not much of it. It serves as filler as you go through the story, which is where the game shines. The puzzles are pretty interesting, such as finding the patterns, a serious trait of Psychosis. -- Senua I recommend looking at the behind-the-scenes content too, it helps you understand everything that is going on. You'll see how they developed the game, such as recording the voices in Senuas's head, the acting and motion capture. One of the best things is that the developers dedicated time to consulting expert mental health professionals & real people that suffer from Psychosis to make the in-game experience as accurate as possible. Ninja Theory has donated at least $25,000 to mental Health America. The goal of this game is to reaise awareness of mental health, it's definetly worth playing and experiencing for yourself, you won't see anything like this game elsewhere.", "appid": "414340", "steamid": "profiles/76561198184430574", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "14", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1529755200.0}
