{"text": "Alright.  My friends and I spent countless hours playing the original when it released with the OG Xbox. Maybe even into the thousands of hours with co-op, LAN parties, and so on. That said, I had some, I don't know...doubts maybe, as to how well Combat Evolved would really hold up. It definitely held up pretty well, especially considering 343s reskin and your ability to switch between it and the classic look at will. Really provided some old/new contrast. Anyway, Combat Evolved is the introduction of both the series and the original Xbox, as its launch title and hallmark IP; and of course the legendary Master Chief, who you will become for the majority of the remainder of the series. The events in Combat Evolved take place after the events in Reach, and features Captain Keyes having Master Chief woken from cryosleep and teamed up with Cortana, as their ship, the Pillar of Autumn is boarded and captured by the Covenant. Eventually, everyone ends up on the surface of the actual Halo, which holds a dread secret that the Covenant were seeking but didn't understand. The gameplay is basically the same as Reach, although with a mind to the original Combat Evolved controls (meaning they stay true to the individual game's original control scheme, albeit with a better controller button layout). Tight gunplay is there as expected. The pistol is nerfed a little. Beyond that though, all is as it should be. However, Combat Evolved does also feature terrible level design, and that design breaks the game's pacing to an extent that you are often left relatively directionless and among other things can end up with you being completely turned around, wasting time dealing with that. Also, something they learned to do in later installments was keep you from having to backtrack on almost every indoor mission, which you do in fact have to do often and annoyingly, in Combat Evolved. Those are my only real complaints though.  All told, it took me around eight hours to complete the campaign. The audio in Combat Evolved is thankfully much improved from 343s audio debacle with Reach. I only noted two instances where that bug showed up in Combat Evolved (it's a bug that creates the sound quality of blown speakers basically). The voice acting was better than I remembered, and the music is already legendary, so there is that.  The graphics are quality. Actually, the reskin graphics have the same quality as Reach, which is to say, quite modern and colorful. An interesting and very cool design choice though was to add the ability to toggle between that and the classic look with the simply click of a button. As with Reach, 343 has managed to do the original Bungie game justice here, most notably with the significant upgrade to graphical fidelity, but also with what seem to be some positive gameplay tweaks. I feel that, as with Reach, the ten bucks or less you will spend on Combat Evolved on its own is far less than the value the game offers, and honestly, the MP maps in Combat Evolved are fairly legendary as well, adding even more value to the equation.  My Halo: Reach review:", "appid": "1064221", "steamid": "profiles/76561198044602606", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "20", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1586088000.0}
