{"text": "Mount and Blade II: Bannerlord is a prequel to the brilliant Mount and blade: Warband, taking place 200 years before warband. Your parents are killed and you must hunt down the people who sold your younger siblings, and after saving a doctor, gives you a bronze artifact not knowing its true worth Pros: ~This game is absolutely gorgeous compared to Warband, Obviously using a new engine ~a lot of the music is redone from Warband, and generally sounds much better and more genuine ~the battles are a lot better, requiring you to actually use commands, and gives a reason to. Generally, the soldiers on both sides are smarter instead of the usual \"Charge forward with every unit or stand in a line\" ~the introduction of clans is a welcome mechanic, allowing you to own your own clan and have certain jobs for the names characters of your clans, it makes it feel like you have a mini faction from the beginning. ~the map is absolutely massive, it would take you, on average, 30 minutes to get from one end to another. ~Multiplayer, for the most part, is very fun with the addition of siege (which needs a redoing) Skirmish, and Captain, where you control a bunch of AI, and each time you die, you can take over one of your AI members ~The continuation of adding mods allows for a hope as to see how people will create immense mods that completely change the game (looking forward to something like Gekokujo in a few years) Cons: ~The biggest problem is the amount of crashing and problems it faces, though expected in an early access game. For singleplayer, doing certain things might lead to your game crashing, for me, it was manually selling prisoners. For multiplayer, the skirmish mode just does not work for me, as everytime I enter one, the server crashes and im booted back to the menu screen ~I dont really like the drag progression of the new skill mechanic, where doing things like fighting with weapons and riding or running progress as it should, you have mechanics like Leadership or medicine, both arguably the most important skills in Mount and blade, taking HOURS to progress from 15 to 17. All upgrade choices start at LV 25 for skills, but with many of them being very specific and time consuming, such as having extremely high leadership constantly for leadership, it feels almost impossible to do so. ~The shops now all compile into one trade system, which I dont like. If I want to find armor, I have to scroll all the way down from several items to find armor. I feel like it wouldnt be that hard to implement what they did in Warband, where you go to the marketplace, go to the merchant you want, and choose what that merchant has to sell to you in a simpler list. ~Siege mode in multiplayer is completely broken. Over the 8 or so times I played it, only one of those times did the attackers win, the other times, attackers never even got CLOSE to getting past the front gate. OVERALL: 8.5/10 Its a very good game for its release. Yes, it needs a LOT of fixing, yes, the game can be tedious in some points, but in a year or so, I see this surpassing Warband in Vanilla if the devs continue to work on fixing and adding new content. As for modding it, I have no clue how easy or hard it is to do that, but I would love to see custom content. I really have high hopes for this game, as do most people who played Warband and loved it", "appid": "261550", "steamid": "profiles/76561198023173016", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": true, "tstamp_created": 1585656000.0}
