{"text": "Minha análise é a primeira BR, por isso resolvi analisar. O jogo tem 36 conquistas, que você consegue em 15 minutos sem fazer nada. Um ponto muito negativo é que não tem trilha sonora, nenhuma música. Outro ponto negativo é que quando esse pato anda, não tem som os passos dele. Nem os passos do personagem. Basicamente o único som do jogo é os ataques do personagem e dos inimigos. Quando você conversa com algum personagem, nenhum botão que eu apertei deu skip na conversa. Tem que clicar nela com o mouse e a camera fica esquisita. Tem um portal que não consegui entrar. Tem como upar atributos e árvore de skills (não testei). Como arqueiro você pode invocar um Tucano pra bater no bichos, achei isso engraçado kkk Você pode pular, rolar, nadar. Só tem 2 tipos de inimigos, as gomas e os trolls. Pra um jogo de R$2,00 é divertido por uns 5 minutos e pelas conquistas. Mas não recomendo o jogo por não ter música no menu inicial, nem no jogo. E não ter nenhum outro som além dos ataques dos personagens. Isso deixa o jogo meio vazio.", "appid": "1396380", "steamid": "profiles/76561198201902359", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "6", "votes_funny": "2", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1601467200.0}
{"text": "Ставлю дизлайк по нескольким причинам: 1. Как таковой интерактивности нет (только в конце можно сделать выбор). Это просто фильм, где нам нужно кликать для продолжения сюжета. Зачем? Сделали бы просто фильм, ибо к середине когда ты это понимаешь (что это просто фильм и никакой интерактивности нет), тебе становится просто скучно кликать 2. Сюжет, а именно (ВНИМАНИЕ, СПОЙЛЕР) -   И на этом все. Никакого раскрытия персонажей, ничего. Даже ГГ никак не раскрыт, кто он, что он...хз, просто пацан который вырос в бункере, все... 3. Сюжет очень короткий. На 2 часа максимум. P.s. у меня почти 3 из-за того, что я поставил на паузу и отошел по делам. Если вы не готовы платить, то скачайте с торрента. По сути, фильм можно проспидранить и вернуть за него деньги, но по скидочке за 180 рублей в коллекцию взять можно.", "appid": "481110", "steamid": "profiles/76561198076853159", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1577534400.0}
{"text": "I'm a bit late, but some people still don't know about this one. Gotta make sure some of you can read this, so I'll get to the point since the game isn't anything new. Pros and cons strangely work together, I need to work any thoughts left to draw a conclusion and to justify my score.   It is a very enjoyable indie game at first, but quite incomplete or insufficient as you keep going through. Since people tend to get way too emotional, we immediately get to like emotional games so blindly. Once you get to the gameplay you shall notice that whenever a game is way too random, things tend to get unfair or boring or simply illogical/absurd.  But on the other hand, heavy scripted games can become predictable. Well, sometimes you get lucky and the random events collide with minor scripted stuff, then generating interesting situations that can be really surprising and this is when the game shines - until broken connections ruin previous days statements done by the game itself. Do not confuse bad events ruining your plans, with nonsensical violations of basic game rules. You either are under control of your characters or you are not, splitting that in half sounds bad  . These things happen a lot, and sometimes it can be immersion breaking (if anyone even bother living the character) and although rarely, it can be game-breaking too. I was just sleeping, waking up, building small tools and eating to fill my character's needs, obviously wearing off as soon as you jump on it. This is how we can resume this game, you play with a life simulator during the day with zero violent incidents, so you can be ready to go scavenging during the night where violence may or may not happen. During the day, it is incredibly monotonous and only a few specific NPCs and scripts will be calling you out, they're always non-hostile, but the events can take your character down if it was too hard, or up if things go as planned. You don't get to play that part, you just have to use your beautiful imagination as random events unfolds (more likely) negatively. If your shelter is ever attacked, it is down to the old text-based surprises, but they are so randomly generated they're crazy. Since the game can't be complete, it makes sense that half of its features are text-based so I don't see a problem there, my problem here is how this is so weirdly delivered. After surviving my first gameplay, I wanted another run, the game is intriguing and the gameplay can be hella fun if you get the point, gotta be patient and smart to survive, that’s the point. You need your Will Wright’s games experience to make sure you can survive the dice rolling on the text. There is no save-game nor load-game (not really). I was just trying to see how things would evolve or devolve next morning, and next morning and the next, until I could finally see the fraud. Some of you may want to go with the alt+tab trick but I have seen it before, it won't always work. I like the perma-death or permanent consequences - and you should like it too, since well placed random stuff can compose some interesting stories and events that will \"entertain\" you for that matter. Like having hope after something done or losing hope after some tragedy, so that's great. Good luck, may you have the best of it. There was this night we couldn't go out for scavenging because there was some heavy bombing outside. Makes sense, I expected the worst. Someone from my house could die while sleeping under the debris or maybe someone would have a panic attack or something like that. I expected way too much, because on the next morning a text showed up saying... \"Bandits stole these items, Livia got deep wounds.\" Bandits? Stole my stuff during a winter night of heavy bombing?? Then out of the blue a few days later, a character (Zlata) left the shelter. Before I criticize again how weirdly this game has been programmed, I must say Zlata is a good spirited character, her trait that is, and crazy violent events I forced her into may have broken her. But there was no sign warning me of it, she was just ''sad'' for a couple days not really ''depressed'' until rupture. Not because she was very broken emotionally, since that can happen, it didn't look like it. She just left shelter and there was no other force implying the why. Fine, go away, leave your pregnant roommate alone to die. I can pretend I accept that inconsistency. 2 seconds later another text showed up saying... \"Livia has left the shelter\" and the house just stood there completely empty. The pregnant girl left the shelter too. No apparent reason, no emotional breakdown, no warning in previous days. She just left the shelter - they were a band of three but Marko was dead at day 10. With relative success they moved on and kept on going, I even had a revenge mission where they killed poor Marko, also successfully. But they just left on day 25. No warning, no nothing, day 25 the two girls just left the shelter and the house was all empty and the game ended, together with my interest in it, my violated enjoyment and most importantly, my control. It rendered the whole survive-inside-home pointless, since they could have been gone since day 1 with another text-based ending showing the outcome. The game is cheap, so I don't think you are at risk of anything here.   some separated DLCs are still profiting over the base game but I couldn't explore much, it is confusing to understand if the Director Cut got everything or if I must buy the others, the menu is weird but you got some new stories with new characters there. So I don't know if further stories got any better with excessive random stuff breaking logic every 15 minutes. So this is, for lack of neutral scoring, a positive thumb-down just acting as a warning sign for you al things considered. You connect the characters independently of what the game wants to do, or what it can do, so you expect to be in full control of that even if things go down south or upwards, the devs should have guessed that. You must put some limitations of how far a controlled character can really behave out of your bounds if you don't want to look like a cheap randomizer. 5/10", "appid": "282070", "steamid": "profiles/76561198061795684", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "8", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1599480000.0}
