{"text": "More reviews at:  There are some good ideas here, tons of production value, lots of lore, and stuff I like, but unfortunately, the not-quite-free-to-play third-person sci-fi co-op-focused shooter Sellers of the Broken Playerbase has too many crippling design flaws to be anywhere near worthwhile.  Relaunching as actually-free-to-play-this-time under the generic name \"Spacelords\" won't make a difference to anything but playercount, and that too will dwindle unless some serious changes are made. When your game's closest analogue is gameplay-rich Warframe, the poster child for free-to-play done right and shining example of post-launch content, you seriously have your work cut out for you to be anything worth downloading.  Raiders of the Broken Planet leaves me with nothing but a question: WHY? Why is it released as \"free-to-play\" when the free content is just a one-mission demo and the devs even say it's not free-to-play? Why can't I blindfire from cover or shoot from the hip?  Why does hitting the Fire button RELOAD your weapon when not aiming?  Why must I aim to shoot my gun, suffering a movement penalty? Why is there no run button?  Why must I keep moving long enough in a single direction for my character to start running, only to lose all momentum when turning/strafing?  What is this, a GBA-era Metroid game? Why is there no crouch button? Why is there no Warframe-style \"hold Shift to sprint, tap Shift to dodge, tap crouch key to slide\" functionality?  Why are Raiders so incapable of moving with any kind of high mobility? Why would you sell the Campaigns, segmenting what few players actually play this game?  Sellers of the Broken Playerbase, indeed. Why is there only matchmaking in terms of online multiplayer?  Why must I wait around for five minutes to get into a game?  Why can't I look at a server browser?  This was sorted out in 1999.  How do you mess it up today? Why will it only launch a game with four players?  Why does it need the four players to ready up before kicking us back to the menu?  Why can't I run a mission with only two players, maybe on a lower difficulty? Why can't I host a private game, select a difficulty, disable Antagonists, launch with fewer than four players, and get full rewards? Why can't I invite friends, unless I want them, too, to be stuck waiting in a matchmaking lobby, hoping we get placed into a match we can actually finish?  This is entirely the reason I have not, do not, and cannot recommend this game to anyone I know. What is the point of using the purple Invitation tickets if I can only invite people from my Steam Friends List?  Why can't I access a list of Recent Players and invite them?  Using the forums or other external tools to find players is not an excuse, solution, or replacement for functionality that should be there in the first place. Why can I only get full rewards in Matchmaking?  How am I supposed to upgrade my characters and get equipment when even joining a match is a pain? Why do loading screens show the layout of a damn gamepad?  This is a shooter game on PC. Why does playing in solo only earn me in-game money (only once per mission, no less) and not any of the XP or blueprints I need to upgrade my characters? Why must I grind my way past level 60 to unlock all of the characters, and then pay in-game money to access them, when there are only 13 missions to play?  How much grinding do you expect me to do? Why won't it let other players join after one disconnects?  Or are there just so few players that it never pulls anyone in after someone leaves? Why do the weapons feel so weak?  Why do they have such tiny magazines?  Why is ammo capacity so low?  Am I really expected to grind out the basically-unobtainable blueprints to upgrade even the basic weapons? Why do the Raiders only have one weapon, even when the character models have holsters on them?  Where are the sidearms and melee weapons? Why can't Cortez leave in the shuttle to replenish our extra lives during a mission BEFORE our supply of lives run low? Why does it say we left one Raider behind if he disconnected?  Why penalize the rest of us when we're already punished by being down at least one man? Why can Raiders hardly jump, both in terms of height and distance? Why does the tutorial mission do such a bad job at teaching the game's core concepts?  I hit Ctrl assuming it'd make my character crouch, which instead used his special ability, and the tutorial did not properly explain special abilities.  Nor the importance of grappling specific enemies to charge up. Why does the UI/HUD not give enough information about the Aleph-powered enemies the Raiders to need to take out OR the fact that they need to be taken out with melee?  Sure, their outlines can be seen through walls, if they're close enough, but that's not enough.  Think of the warning indicators in Valve games.  Without enough information, missions like Short-Fused are damn near impossible. Why have a rock/paper/scissors melee system when it often ends in one-hit-kills, penalizing the entire party because one player got insta-grappled by an Aleph'd-up enemy? Why place so much emphasis on a melee system when closing to melee range is a chore, due to the lack of manual sprinting, lacklustre dodging, and lack of evasive jumps (comboing a knee slide into a jump to leap forward, for example)? Why is there only console-style Hold Aim with no option for PC-style Toggle Aim? Why must players battle with each other on the rewards screen for a chance to get items after running a mission?  Why can't we all just get the rewards? Why does it need to be this infuriating to get blueprints: wait in Matchmaking for the mission that drops the blueprint to start, hope enough people join, hope they all ready up, hope there's no Antagonist, hope the difficulty is manageable, hope the players know what they're doing, hope we can finish it, hope the blueprint you want shows up in the rewards screen, and hope you get chosen to receive the blueprint; upon failure, start all over again.  Why would you do this? Why is our communication limited to four emotes and four pictograms, all of which are preset and cannot be customized?  Why is there no text chat or mic support?  Why are there no Counter-Strike/Team Fortress-style Z/X/C communication menus, seeing as how the characters are all voiced, anyway? Why is the connection so bad whenever it makes me Host?  How am I hosting when I can't choose any settings, anyway?  Aren't we just connecting to the game's servers? Why am I penalized for voting to surrender in a mission where my ping is >999, I can't see any of the other players, and I'm essentially doing an impossible mission alone?  How is that my fault?  I just want to play through these damn Campaigns and get some blueprints if at all possible. Why do certain cosmetic character models cost upwards of $20?  No excuse is good enough for this.  $20 is enough to buy a whole other game. Why are the character designs either rejected Mad Max extras or oversexualized Warframe wannabes?  Why does every character feel like it was designed to appeal to someone's fetish? Why do the alternate character models not show up in cutscenes or profile icons in the menus if we have purchased them?  They still have animated faces so the dialogue should still work.  Why do they cost so much if they only appear during gameplay? Why is there so much simulated shaky-cam in cutscenes? Why do I need to farm blueprints to upgrade weapons, rather than just use in-game resources like Faction points and in-game money? Why can I only equip one Player Card modification at a time, and why it is one chosen at random from the ones I've tried to equip?  Why can't I just equip multiple mod cards like in Warframe and actually get the impression my character is getting stronger? Why even bother with Spacelords at all? Play Warframe instead.", "appid": "436180", "steamid": "profiles/76561197976188556", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "14", "votes_funny": "2", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1532952000.0}
