{"text": "Delivery-Boy Simulator 1995. No bikes, fast travel, or sprint buttons in these here parts! Legend of Miro is touted as a story-rich game, however most of the story is locked behind an abundance of filler content:  *numerous* fetch quests which backtrack multiple screens at a leisurely pace, mini-games such as guessing a random number or inputting the correct directions to gather materials, and rather slow battles (it took me several minutes to wear down the very first enemy i faced - the battle wasn't challenging, just lengthy).  All of this repetition seems designed to pad the game with extra hours of gameplay, and may start to feel overly grindy.  This is best demonstrated by an excerpt from my experience with the game: --- MINOR SPOILER ALERT AHEAD    Townsperson: 'Hey, what's up with that cave?  Go find out for me!' Me: 'I'm on it!'  (2 minute walk to cave) Cave:  Nope!  You'll need   to progress. Me: 'I'm on it!' (2 minute walk to town) Townsperson:  'Hey, go see the blacksmith for that  !' Me: 'I'm on it!' (1 minute walk to blacksmith) Blacksmith:  'Hey, if you want a  , go back to that cave to get me some  !' Me: 'I'm on it!' (2 minute walk to cave, #2) (5 minutes of   via following arrows) Me:  Phew!  I got me some  ! (2 minute walk to town) Blacksmith:  Cool beans, here's a  !  Now go do that cave thing! Me: I'm on it! (2 minute walk to cave, #3) Soldier:  Nope!  Fight me first! (5 minute battle)   Me:  Phew, finally! NOW I'm on it! (5 minutes exploring cave)   Cave:  Whoops, did you forget to tell that first townsperson you now had a   and could explore me?  Ha, you're getting nothing til then! Me: Doh...guess I'm on it! (2 minute walk to town) Townsperson:  Great!  You got a  !  Now go explore that cave for reals! Me:  I'm on it! (2 minute walk to cave, #4) (2 minutes exploring cave later:) Cave:  Haha, got you again!  You'll also need a  ! Me:  I'm on it! (2 minute walk to town) Blacksmith: Ok, here's a  .  Try that cave one more time? Me:  I'm on it! (2 minute walk to cave, #5) Cave:  Oh, fine.  Here's your reward: 3 sentences of new story tidbits! Me:  .   ..   ...  ......30 minutes... for that?  Screw you, cave.  Screw you. --- (END MINOR SPOILER ALERT)    Legend of Miro has potential, but relies too heavily on tedious 'filler' gameplay to fully succeed as a story-centric game.  There are also some minor technical issues present in the game, but the super-friendly developer seems to be extremely active, fixing these whenever they appear.  The extraordinary helpfulness demonstrated by the developer is a definite plus, but may not make up for the game's slooooow pacing, which was my largest issue.  As it stands, I could only recommend this title to   patient gamers.", "appid": "469980", "steamid": "profiles/76561198012248506", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "33", "votes_funny": "8", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1472299200.0}
